  <static seed="1600" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalEquations/solveRationalEquations70.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{x+6}{x+1}-\frac{9}{x+9}} = -3 }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="34" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{-3,-6\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To get rid of fractions, we multiply each term in this equation by the common denominator, which is <m>{\left(x+1\right)\mathopen{}\left(x+9\right)}</m> in this example.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \amp {\frac{x+6}{x+1}-\frac{9}{x+9}} = -3 \\
   \amp {\frac{x+6}{x+1}\mathopen{}\left(x+1\right)\mathopen{}\left(x+9\right)-\frac{9}{x+9}\mathopen{}\left(x+1\right)\mathopen{}\left(x+9\right)} ={-3\mathopen{}\left(x+1\right)\mathopen{}\left(x+9\right)} \\
   \amp {\left(x+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(x+9\right)-9\mathopen{}\left(x+1\right)} = {-3\mathopen{}\left(x^{2}+10x+9\right)} \\
   \amp {x^{2}+15x+54-9x-9} = {-\left(3x^{2}+30x+27\right)} \\
   \amp {x^{2}+6x+45} = {-\left(3x^{2}+30x+27\right)} \\
   \amp {x^{2}+6x+45+3x^{2}+30x+27} = 0 \\
   \amp {4x^{2}+36x+72} = 0 \\
   \amp {4\mathopen{}\left(x^{2}+9x+18\right)} = 0 \\
   \amp {4\mathopen{}\left(x+3\right)\mathopen{}\left(x+6\right)} = 0 \\
   \amp {x+3}=0 \:\: or\:\: {x+6}=0 \\
   \amp x=-3 \:\: or\:\: x=-6
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p><alert>Checking</alert></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. In the original equation, both denominators cannot be <m>0</m>. We set them to <m>0</m>, so we can find out what values to exclude from the solution set.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \amp x+1 = 0 \amp \;\amp  x+9=0 \\
   \amp x=-1 \amp \;\amp  x=-9
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must exclude <m>-1</m> and <m>-9</m> from the solution set, so the final solution is <m>x=-3</m> and <m>x=-6</m>.</p>
</solution>
